alert.note: Alert for Clallam (Washington) Issued by the National Weather Service

info.headline: Flood Warning issued December 05 at 9:43AM PST until December 05 at 7:35PM PST by NWS Seattle
info.description: ...Forecast flooding changed to Minor severity and increased in duration for the following rivers in Washington... Bogachiel River Near La Push affecting Clallam County. ...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in Washington... Nisqually River Near National affecting Lewis and Pierce Counties. Chehalis River Above Doty affecting Lewis County. .Heavy rain will continue in the Washington Cascades through this afternoon. Another 1 to 3 inches of rain is forecast before the rain rates ease. For the Olympic Peninsula Region...including La Push, McDonald Bridge, Sequim, Potlatch, Satsop, Montesano...Moderate flooding is forecast. For the South West Region...including Mud Mtn. Dam Outflow, R Street Bridge, South Prairie, Fairfax, Orting, Puyallup, National, McKenna, Rainier, Packwood, Randle, Mayfield Dam...Moderate flooding is forecast. For the Chehalis River Basin Region...including Bucoda, Centralia, Chehalis, Doty, Centralia, Grand Mound, Porter...Moderate flooding is forecast. ...FLOOD WARNING NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast. * WHERE...Bogachiel River near La Push. * WHEN...Until this evening. * IMPACTS...At 37.0 feet, the Bogachiel River will cause flooding of State Highway 110 near the Bogachiel bridge...closing the road. * ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 8:30 AM PST Tuesday the stage was 38.3 feet. - Flood stage is 37.0 feet. - Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours ending at 8:30 AM PST Tuesday was 39.0 feet. - Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage late this morning and continue falling. - Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of 37.1 feet on 12/10/2004. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood &&
info.instruction: Turn around, don`t drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood deaths occur in vehicles. Motorists should not attempt to drive around barricades or drive cars through flooded areas. Caution is urged when walking near riverbanks. Additional information is available at www.weather.gov. The next statement will be issued by this afternoon at 545 PM PST.
